T1  - The gender agenda in Indo-Fijian wedding songs
AN  - 1808454103
AB  - There are stereotyped depictions of women in songs called Vivah ke Geet (songs of weddings) performed by female folksingers in the Indo-Fijian community of the Sanatani sect, which is one of the dominant religious groups among Indo-Fijians and the only demographically prominent sect that actually practises wedding song performances. These songs are performed for pre-wedding functions and wedding ceremonies, a ceremony composed of several fragmented rituals. A close reading of these songs exposes patriarchal ideologies, female and male stereotypes and socially sanctioned codes of behaviour and appearance to be imposed on individuals through this medium. Fundamentally, the discussion weaves together three voices to provide insight into the gendered nature of Indo-Fijian society. The first voice is that of Judith Butler and her theoretical construct of performativity. The second voice is that of the wedding singers and their opinions and the third voice(s) is that of the relations of brides and grooms who speak through the singers' lyrics.
